The carbon cycle may be thrown off and temperature rises can occur due to environmental changes (Maestrini et al., 2017). Recent writing has characterized climate inequality as a complex problem. Carbon dioxide emissions are regarded by conservationists as the primary source of pollution which in turn leads to rising temperatures and other climatic anomalies (J. S. Liu et al., 2013). Environmental carbon footprints account for over 81% of greenhouse gas releases (Saranga, 2009). Physical, physiological, and ecological consequences may result from it such as severe weather events including periods of drought, storms, and heat shocks; the elevation of ocean levels; and the depletion of natural resources (Olesen et al., 2015). Increases in the production of greenhouse gases risk having far-reaching consequences for animal and plant life The United Nations' Sustainable Development Goal aimed to improve the quality of life for all people everywhere while also preventing the acceleration of environmental degradation. The core strategy plan for government entities should focus on improving environmental quality and achieving sustainable growth (Ullah et al., 2020). Therefore, for economic development to be sustainable, officials need to pinpoint the key economic factors causing ecological concerns (see Table 1â3


